COMPONENT 0 — EMAIL INGESTION PIPELINE
REWRITTEN AGAINST MASTER ARCHITECTURE

---

WHAT THIS COMPONENT DOES IN SIMPLE TERMS

Component 0 is the front door of ContextIQ. Everything starts here. It connects to Outlook mailboxes, pulls emails securely, cleans them, strips and pseudonymises PII, stores them in PostgreSQL, seeds the knowledge graph in Neo4j, and queues them for intelligence processing via Celery.

No commitment extraction happens here. No contradiction detection. No AI reasoning. This component's only job is to get clean, secure, structured email data into your system reliably. Everything else depends on this being solid.

Think of it like a water treatment plant. Raw water comes in. It gets filtered, cleaned, and made safe. Then it flows to the rest of the city. If the treatment plant is broken, nothing downstream works.

---

ROI OF COMPONENT 0

This component has no direct business output. Users never see it working. But its ROI is foundational.

Without it — zero emails in the system. Every other component starves.

With it done well — every other component gets clean, consistent, secure data without worrying about where it came from or whether it's safe to process. That separation of concerns is what makes the rest of the system buildable by one person without going insane.

For interviews — being able to explain your ingestion architecture shows you understand production systems, not just AI models. Most candidates who build AI projects skip this layer entirely and use static CSV files. You don't. That distinction matters.

---

WHO ELSE DOES THIS AND HOW

Microsoft Copilot — native access. No API needed. It lives inside Microsoft 365 and reads mailboxes directly. You can't replicate this without being Microsoft.

Zapier and Make — use Microsoft Graph API with OAuth exactly like you will. No-code tools but identical underlying mechanism. Their ingestion is shallow — they trigger on new emails but don't do deep thread reconstruction or PII handling.

Nylas — a commercial email API abstraction layer that sits on top of Microsoft Graph API and Gmail API simultaneously. Handles OAuth complexity for you. Worth knowing about for interviews — "I could have used Nylas but chose to implement Graph API directly for deeper control and to avoid vendor dependency."

Your advantage over all of these — none of them pseudonymise PII at ingestion time, build knowledge graph nodes for every email, or feed into a governance layer. You do all three simultaneously.

---

FULL PIPELINE STEP BY STEP

Step 1 — Workspace and Mailbox Registration

Before any email is touched, a workspace must exist and a mailbox must be registered to it. This is the entry point for all data.

A Workspace Admin logs into ContextIQ and creates a workspace. This writes one row to the workspace table in PostgreSQL. It also creates a namespace in Neo4j for this workspace — every graph node and edge for this workspace will carry this namespace, preventing cross-tenant data leakage.

The admin then registers an Outlook mailbox. This triggers the OAuth 2.0 flow via MSAL. The user logs into Microsoft's login page, grants Mail.Read permission, and MSAL returns an access token and refresh token. Both are immediately encrypted using Azure Key Vault before being stored in the mailbox table. Raw tokens never touch your database.

A workspace_user record is created for the admin with role ADMIN. Audit log entry written — action MAILBOX_ADDED, resource mailbox, outcome SUCCESS.

Step 2 — Initial Email Fetch

First time a mailbox is registered, fetch all existing emails. This is the historical backfill.

Call Microsoft Graph API endpoint — https://graph.microsoft.com/v1.0/me/messages with parameters $top equals 50, $orderby equals sentDateTime desc, $select equals id,subject,body,from,toRecipients,ccRecipients,sentDateTime,conversationId,conversationIndex,importance,hasAttachments.

Why $select — only request the fields you need. Reduces payload size, reduces latency, reduces cost.

Why $top equals 50 — fetch in pages of 50 to avoid rate limiting. Microsoft Graph API allows up to 999 per page but 50 is safer for a portfolio project and easier to process in memory.

Use delta query from the first fetch — store the deltaToken returned by Microsoft. Every subsequent fetch uses this token to get only new or changed emails since the last sync. This is your incremental sync mechanism.

Step 3 — PII Detection and Pseudonymisation

Every email body passes through Microsoft Presidio before anything else happens. This is the security gate. No email content touches your database in raw form until PII is handled.

Presidio's AnalyzerEngine scans the text for PII entities — person names, email addresses, phone numbers, credit card numbers, national IDs, dates of birth, addresses.

For each detected PII entity — generate a UUID token. Store the mapping in the pii_vault table — original value encrypted with AES-256 via Azure Key Vault, token stored in the main column. Replace the PII in the email body with the token.

Example — "Sarah Johnson will deliver the report" becomes "USR_7f3a9b will deliver the report."

The sender email address in the from field is also tokenised. Same for recipients and CC fields. Every person reference in your system is a token from this point forward.

Store the pseudonymised body as body_clean. Store the original body encrypted as body_raw_encrypted. The original is kept only for audit purposes with strict access controls.

Step 4 — Email Cleaning

After PII pseudonymisation, clean the email body further.

Use BeautifulSoup to strip HTML tags from emails sent in HTML format. Most Outlook emails are HTML under the hood.

Use email-reply-parser to remove quoted previous emails from reply chains. Each email should only contain the new content added by the sender, not the entire history of the thread repeated.

Strip common signature patterns — text following "Regards,", "Thanks,", "Best,", "Sincerely," followed by a name pattern.

Strip legal disclaimers — long blocks of text containing phrases like "This email and any attachments are confidential" are boilerplate and carry no business information.

What remains after cleaning is body_clean — the actual meaningful content of this specific email, pseudonymised and stripped of noise. This is what every downstream component receives.

Step 5 — Thread Reconstruction

Microsoft gives you a conversationId for each email. All emails sharing the same conversationId belong to the same thread.

Check if a thread_id already exists in your email_thread table for this conversationId. If yes — this email is a reply in an existing thread. Update last_email_at and email_count on the thread record. If no — this is the first email in a new thread. Create a new email_thread record.

Store the email in email_message table with the thread_id foreign key linking it to its thread.

Step 6 — Entity Extraction for Thread Linking

Run spaCy's named entity recognition on body_clean to extract entities — dates, person names as tokens, organisation names, locations, project-like noun phrases.

For each extracted entity — check if it already exists in thread_entity table for this workspace. If yes — update last_mentioned_at and mention_count. If no — create new thread_entity record.

This builds the entity index that Component 0's cross-thread linking uses. When two threads mention the same entity — "June 24" appears in Thread A and Thread B — they become candidates for thread relationship detection.

Run thread relationship candidate detection using rules — do any existing threads share entities with this new email's thread? If yes, create thread_relationship records with detection_method RULE_BASED and appropriate confidence scores. No LLM involved here.

Step 7 — Knowledge Graph Seeding

For every email processed, write corresponding nodes and edges to Neo4j.

Create or update Person node for sender — properties token, display_name, email_domain, workspace_id.
Create or update Thread node if new thread — properties thread_id, subject, workspace_id.
Create email_message node — properties message_id, sent_at, workspace_id.
Create SENT edge from Person to Thread — person sent an email in this thread.
Create INVOLVES edges from Thread to every recipient Person node.
Create MENTIONS edges from Thread to any Topic nodes matching extracted entities.

Store the Neo4j node IDs back in your PostgreSQL records — kg_node_id columns. This gives you direct graph lookups without additional matching logic later.

Step 8 — Queue for Intelligence Processing

After successful storage in PostgreSQL and Neo4j, publish a Celery task to the intelligence queue.

Task payload — message_id, thread_id, workspace_id, project_id if already assigned.

Component 1 — commitment extraction — picks this task up asynchronously. Component 0 is done. It doesn't wait for extraction to complete. Fire and forget into the queue.

Write sync_log entry — emails_fetched, emails_processed, emails_failed, cost_tokens_used, status SUCCESS or PARTIAL.

Step 9 — Incremental Sync Scheduling

After initial backfill, schedule incremental syncs using Celery Beat.

Default sync frequency — every 15 minutes per mailbox. Configurable per workspace.

Each sync uses the stored delta_token to fetch only emails changed since last sync. Update delta_token after each successful sync.

Handle Microsoft Graph API errors gracefully —
429 Too Many Requests — exponential backoff, retry after Retry-After header value.
401 Unauthorised — token expired, refresh via MSAL, retry once. If refresh fails, mark mailbox sync_status as TOKEN_EXPIRED and alert workspace admin.
503 Service Unavailable — Microsoft outage, retry with exponential backoff up to 3 times then mark as SYNC_FAILED.

