---

BLOCKERS YOU WILL HIT AND HOW TO SOLVE THEM

Blocker 1 — OAuth flow is confusing to set up the first time.
Solution — follow Microsoft's official Python quickstart for Graph API exactly. Register your app in Azure Portal, get Client ID, Client Secret, Tenant ID. Set redirect URI to http://localhost:8000/auth/callback for development. Don't try to understand every OAuth concept before starting. Get it working first.

Blocker 2 — Presidio false positives. It flags things as PII that aren't. For example — "Python" might get flagged as a person name.
Solution — configure Presidio with a custom deny list of technical terms and product names. Tune the confidence threshold — only pseudonymise entities where Presidio confidence is above 0.7. Accept that some false positives will occur and document this as a known limitation.

Blocker 3 — Neo4j and PostgreSQL writes need to be atomic. If PostgreSQL write succeeds but Neo4j write fails, your data is inconsistent.
Solution — implement a two phase approach. Write to PostgreSQL first with kg_synced equals false. Then write to Neo4j. If Neo4j succeeds, update kg_synced to true. A background reconciliation job runs hourly — finds all records where kg_synced is false and retries Neo4j write. Eventual consistency rather than strict atomicity. Document this tradeoff explicitly.

Blocker 4 — spaCy model download in Docker.
Solution — add RUN python -m spacy download en_core_web_sm to your Dockerfile. This downloads the model during image build, not at runtime.

Blocker 5 — Celery tasks failing silently.
Solution — always log task start, task success, and task failure with structlog in every Celery task function. Set up a dead letter queue in your Celery config. Monitor queue depth in your metrics. A task that fails silently means emails never get processed and you won't know.

Blocker 6 — Email body encoding issues. Emails arrive in various encodings — UTF-8, Latin-1, Windows-1252. Non-UTF-8 characters cause crashes.
Solution — always decode email bodies with errors equals replace parameter. Add body_encoding column to email_message table recording detected encoding. Log encoding issues for monitoring.

Blocker 7 — Azure Key Vault cold start latency. First request to Key Vault after idle period takes 2 to 3 seconds.
Solution — warm up Key Vault connection on application startup. Cache frequently used keys in memory for 5 minutes using Redis. Never call Key Vault on the hot path of a user-facing API request.

---

HOW AI LAST PRINCIPLE SHOWS UP IN COMPONENT 0

Component 0 is entirely rule based and deterministic. Zero LLM calls. Zero AI.

Thread grouping — rule. Microsoft conversationId groups emails. No AI needed.
PII detection — Microsoft Presidio is a rule based NLP tool with ML models underneath but no LLM. Not generative AI. Fast, deterministic, auditable.
Entity extraction — spaCy NER is a statistical NLP model, not an LLM. Lightweight, local, fast, free.
Thread linking — four deterministic rules. Entity overlap, same project, same type, temporal proximity. No AI.
Email cleaning — rules and regex. No AI.

This entire component processes emails without spending a single Azure OpenAI token. Your LLM budget is preserved entirely for Components 1 through 4 where AI genuinely earns its place.

---

HOW GMAIL EXTENSIBILITY SHOWS UP HERE

app/ingestion/providers/base.py defines the abstract interface. OutlookProvider implements it. GmailProvider stub exists but raises NotImplementedError.

Every other file in the ingestion folder — cleaner.py, thread_builder.py, entity_extractor.py, thread_linker.py — receives standardised EmailMessage objects. They have no idea whether the email came from Outlook or Gmail.

If you implemented GmailProvider, you would change exactly one line — the provider instantiation in ingestion_tasks.py. Nothing else changes.

---

CONCEPTS TO STUDY IN ORDER OF PRIORITY

First — OAuth 2.0 flow. Understand authorisation code flow, access tokens, refresh tokens, scopes. One day. Microsoft's own documentation explains this specifically for Graph API.

Second — REST APIs and HTTP. GET POST PUT DELETE. Request headers. JSON responses. Status codes — 200 success, 400 bad request, 401 unauthorised, 429 rate limited, 503 unavailable. Half a day.

Third — SQLAlchemy basics. How to define a model class. How to create a session. How to add, query, update records. One day with their official tutorial.

Fourth — Alembic migrations. How to create a migration. How to run it. How to roll back. Half a day.

Fifth — Docker and Docker Compose. What a container is. What a Dockerfile does. How docker-compose.yml defines multiple services. One day of hands on practice — run PostgreSQL and Redis in Docker locally before writing any code.

Sixth — Celery basics. What a task is. How to define one. How to call it asynchronously. How to monitor it. Half a day with their quickstart guide.

Seventh — spaCy NER basics. What named entity recognition is. How to run it on a string. What entity types are available. Half a day.

Eighth — Microsoft Presidio. How to run the analyzer. How to run the anonymizer. How to configure custom entity types. One day hands on.

Ninth — pytest basics. How to write a test function. How to use fixtures. How to mock external dependencies with unittest.mock. One day.

Tenth — structlog. How to configure it. How to add context to log entries. How to output JSON logs. Half a day.

---

WHAT YOU SHOULD BE ABLE TO DO AFTER BUILDING COMPONENT 0

Run docker-compose up and have all services start cleanly.
Register a workspace and mailbox through your API.
Watch emails flow from Outlook into PostgreSQL automatically.
Verify PII is pseudonymised in body_clean.
Verify nodes exist in Neo4j browser.
Verify Celery tasks appear in the intelligence queue.
Run pytest and see green tests.
Open Azure Portal and see your application running.

